:::summary
Johann Sebastian Bach (1685–1750) was the supreme master of Baroque music and, by the judgment of most musicians and critics, the greatest composer who ever lived. A Lutheran church musician who spent most of his career in relative obscurity, Bach produced a body of work — the *Brandenburg Concertos*, the *St. Matthew Passion*, the *Well-Tempered Clavier*, the *Mass in B Minor*, the *Goldberg Variations*, and hundreds of cantatas and organ works — that represents the summit of contrapuntal technique and the deepest musical expression of Christian faith. Largely forgotten after his death, he was rediscovered in the 19th century and recognized as the foundation upon which all subsequent Western classical music rests.
:::

